  &lt;p id="6aJOYR"&gt;OpenAI has been showing some of its customers a new multimodal AI model that can both talk to you and recognize objects, according to a &lt;a href="https://www.theinformation.com/articles/openai-develops-ai-voice-assistant-as-it-chases-google-apple?rc=r6gev9"&gt;new report from &lt;em&gt;The Information&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Citing unnamed sources who’ve seen it, the outlet says this could be part of what the company &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/5/10/24153421/openai-chatgpt-google-search-competitor-service-io"&gt;plans to show on Monday&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="XgPXkn"&gt;The new model reportedly offers faster, more accurate interpretation of images and audio than what its existing separate transcription and text-to-speech models can do&lt;em&gt;. &lt;/em&gt;It would apparently be able to help customer service agents “better understand the intonation of callers’ voices or whether they’re being sarcastic,” and “theoretically,” the model can help students with math or translate real-world signs, writes &lt;em&gt;The Information.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
